Huizinga, Dolan, and van der Molen (2006) investi-
gated developmental changes in set switching and set 
maintenance and sought to determine how EF compo-
nents (i.e., working memory, shifting, and inhibition) 
contributed to observed changes on WCST performance. 
Results showed that adult levels of performance were 
reached in 11-year-olds for set switching and in 15-year-olds 
for set maintenance. Principal component analysis 
revealed that set switching and set maintenance loaded on 
two factors for 7-year-olds, but loaded on a single factor 
in the other age groups. Analyses of (co)variance revealed 
a continuation of EF development into adolescence. 
Confirmatory factor analysis yielded two common  factors: 
working memory and shifting. The variables assumed to 
tap inhibition proved unrelated. Regression analyses were 
