anterior cingulate cortex played a crucial role in EF, while 
Menon and Uddin (2010) found evidence from network 
analysis suggesting a critical role for the insula, particu-
larly the anterior division, in high-level cognitive control 
and attentional processes. Vandewalle et al. (2009) found 
that under conditions of sleep deprivation, individuals 
recruited supplemental anterior frontal, temporal, and 
subcortical regions, while EF was maintained. Huey et al. 
(2009) concluded that “the neuroanatomic findings fron-
totemporal dementia … and patients with corticobasal 
syndrome (CBS) show disparate performance on higher-
order EF” and that “It may be difficult to distinguish 
motor and visuospatial ability from EF in patients with 
CBS using tests with significant motor and visuospatial 
demands such as Trail Making” (p. 453). Therefore, it 
is likely that specificity regarding a hypothesized EF 
component and a specific neuropsychological measure 
cannot be obtained. Simply stated, neuropsychological 
tests are sensitive to a combination of central executive 
(CE) and cognitive functions and have little to say about 
the hypothesized subcomponents.
 ARE TESTS OF EXECUTIVE FUNCTION 
MEASURING A CENTRAL EXECUTIVE? 
Baddeley (1996) described the evolving concept of CE as 
“a unified system with multiple functions, or simply as an 
agglomeration of independent though interacting control 
processes” (p. 5). Barkley (1997) described the CE as an 
amalgam of four executive neuropsychological functions 
that appear to depend on inhibition for their “effective 
execution: (a) working memory, (b) self-regulation of 
affect–motivation–arousal, (c) internalization of speech, 
and (d) reconstitution (behavioral analysis and synthesis)” 
(p. 65). As we have indicated, neuropsychological tests of 
EF do not purely measure specific components of EF. 
Might they be measuring the functioning of the CE defined 
herein as an integrated network of self-regulatory cogni-
tive activity comprising components of working memory, 
attention, reward circuitry, and internalized speech? 
Looking from this perspective, Miyake et al. (2000) 
examined the separability of three often-postulated EF—
mental set shifting (“shifting”), information updating 
and monitoring (“updating”), and inhibition of prepo-
tent responses (“inhibition”) and their roles in complex 
frontal lobe or executive tasks. Confirmatory factor anal-
ysis indicated that the three target EFs were moderately 
correlated to one another but were separable, contribut-
ing differentially to performance on complex executive 
tasks. The results suggested the importance of recogniz-
ing both the unity and diversity of EFs. 
Lehto, Koostra, and Pulkkinen (2003), investigating 
dimensions of EF in 8- to 13-year-old children, found 
modest correlations among EF measures. Both exploratory 
and confirmatory factor analyses yielded three interrelated 
factors, which resembled those obtained by Miyake et al. 
(2000), and which, after some difficulty, were labeled work-
ing memory, inhibition, and shifting. Age correlated with 
performance on most individual EF measures as well as 
measures of shifting and working memory. 
Taken collectively, these studies indicate that there are 
several global and interrelated skills—working memory, 
shifting, and with all probability, inhibiting—that are 
commonly assessed by neuropsychological tests that 
purport to assess EF. While some tests assess one or the 
other factor more strongly, there do not appear to be any 
tests that assess one factor specifically. Although these 
executive factors are separable, they operate in unison on 
most tasks. Even if we wished to evaluate the compo-
nents separately, there remains a legitimate question as 
to the functional utility of doing so. Latent class analysis 
(Miyake et al., 2000) strongly suggests the existence of a 
general EF that reflects the efficiency and perhaps auto-
maticity of the executive management system. 
 IS THE ASSESSMENT OF EXECUTIVE 
FUNCTION ECOLOGICALLY VALID? 
As Barkley and Murphy (2010) point out, there is consid-
erable difficulty in demonstrating ecological validity of 
neuropsychological tests of EF. It is difficult to see how 
brief tests of a few minutes to at most 30 minutes can 
capture such sustained EF in a manner that is ecologi-
cally valid. Some studies (Burgess, Alderman, Evans, 
Emslie, & Wilson, 1998; Kafer & Hunter, 1997) have 
demonstrated that neuropsychological tests measure 
 constructs that are not related to the functional behaviors 
associated with EFs or the latent neuropsychological 
construct hypothetically assessed by the instrument. 
Kafer and Hunter suggest that neuropsychological tests 
for EF are constructed using face validity alone.
Alderman, Burgess, Knight, and Henman (2003) and 
Shallice and Burgess (1991) failed to find a significant or 
meaningful relationship between neuropsychological 
tests and EF rating scales, indicating that whatever it was 
that neuropsychological tests were evaluating, it was not 
behavior as reported by patients with frontal-lobe 
 dysfunction and related executive problems, or direct eval-
uation of EF in everyday life. Burgess and Alderman 
(2003), in discussing the assessment of EF in children, 
concluded “that ideal assessment would obviously attempt 
to assess all of the [common symptoms of dysexecutive 
syndrome] as well as the less common signs of [EDF]. 
However, this is impractical in most clinical settings as 
formal assessment measures do not exist for many of the 
symptoms. Moreover, little is known about what many of 
the tests shown to be sensitive to frontal lobe lesions are 
actually measuring in these cases” (p. 187). 
