 IS THERE AGREEMENT AS TO THE 
COMPONENT PARTS OF THE EXECUTIVE 
CONTROL SYSTEM? 
Because there is no universally accepted definition of EF 
and there is no universal agreement as to its component 
parts, there is considerable ambiguity regarding our knowl-
edge of the development of these skills. Some (Della Sala, 
Grey, Spinnler, & Trivelli, 1998) think of EF as a more uni-
tary executive, while others (Alexander & Stuss, 2000) view 
it as multiple process-related systems. Still others (Wiebe 
et al., 2011) view it as initially undifferentiated by slowly 
evolving constituent subsystems. In reviewing the literature 
on the development of EF in children, Anderson (2002) 
took this second approach and conceptualized four 
 systems—attentional control, information processing, cog-
nitive flexibility, and goal setting—and reviewed the devel-
opment of each of these skills. Most studies that evaluated 
the development of EF skills used either three-factor or 
four-factor models to look at component skills analysis.
 IS THERE A PREDICTABLE NEOTENIC 
SEQUENCE TO THE DEVELOPMENT OF 
EXECUTIVE FUNCTION SKILLS? 
There is substantial evidence that the development of 
executive regulation reflects the neotenic development of 
the executive control system and its component parts 
(Fuster, 1997). Welsh et al. (1991), studying children aged 
3 to 12 years old and using measures that clustered into 
three different factors reflecting speeded responding, set 
maintenance, and planning, found three distinct develop-
mental stages for the development of EF skills: age 6 was 
characterized by competence with visual-motor search 
activities and simple planning routines; age 10 was char-
acterized by set maintenance and hypothesis testing and 
control of impulses; and adolescence involved complex 
planning and verbal fluency. The ages identified were 
when the adult level of performance was obtained. The 
researchers posited that the most EF development occurs 
in middle childhood, with the process continuing into 
adulthood. The available neuropsychological literature 
does not include a thorough

