INTEGRATED MODEL OF EF IN CHILDREN  93
measuring EF on a particular neuropsychological task, 
can we ever say anything about the executive indepen-
dently of the task we use to assess it? Neuropsychology 
has assumed that such conclusions are possible. Burgess 
et al. (1998) found neuropsychological tests loading 
 differentially on three underlying cognitive factors (inhi-
bition, intentionality, and executive memory), supporting 
the conclusions that “different tests measure different 
 cognitive processes, and that there may be limits to the 
fractionation of the executive system” (p. 547). In other 
words, fractionalizing the concept of EF beyond these 
three rather broad categories could not be scientifically 
supported. Perhaps fractionalization itself is question-
able because the three factors act interdependently. 
Chaytor & Schmitter-Edgecombe (2007) found that 
behavioral inhibition, goal-directed behavior/intentional-
ity, and executive memory/cognition were key underlying 
factors of the functional dysexecutive syndrome identi-
fied by checklists. Remaining factors were divergent. 
They concluded that consistent with prior research, the 
dysexecutive syndrome is multifactorial. Just because 
 factors are identifiable does not mean that they operate 
independently. 
These data indicate these dissociable factors do not 
operate totally independently of each other and are in 
fact related to a latent CE factor that is always opera-
tional in tasks requiring executive management. Garon, 
Bryson, and Smith (2008) argued that this was exactly the 
case. “During the last 2 decades, major advances have 
been made in understanding the development of execu-
tive functions (EFs) in early childhood. The EF literature 
during the preschool period using an integrative frame-
work considers EF to be a unitary construct with  partially 
dissociable components (Miyake et al., 2000); working 
memory, response inhibition, and shifting. The CE is 
conceived of as a central attention system that is involved 
in all EF component operations. Research to date  suggests 
that elementary forms of the core EF components are 
present early during the preschool period. Changes in EF 
during the latter half of the preschool period appear to 
be due to the development of attention and integration 
of component EFs” (Garon et al., p. 31). 
Evidence from graph-theoretical analysis suggests that 
traditional neuropsychological fractionalization is not 
consistent with modern theoretical analysis of complex 
brain system functioning. In their review of graphical 
analysis of connectionist models of cognition, Bullmore 
and Sporns (2009) suggest that complex cognitive func-
tioning is best represented by a connectionist small-world 
model of neural networks. Although a complete discus-
sion of these models is beyond the scope of this review, 
small-world neural network models are based on the 
 concept of nodes, which represent the confluence or 
 connectivity points of neurons. Nodes cluster together in 
small networks and vary to the degree of how central 
they are to the connections to other small clustered 
 networks within the system. The most central of network 
nodes are referred to as hubs, which represent key collec-
tion and distributions points. Analyzing the function any 
one node or hub within such a network might have some 
particular research interest but probably less clinical 
 utility. In these models, EF would be best measured by 
the efficiency of the overall network in processing infor-
mation. In other words, fractionalization would have 
little practical utility. To be ecologically valid, neuropsy-
chological measures would have to assess the efficiency of 
the entire system and might require recalibration to 
accomplish this task. Some research (Zelazo et al., 1997) 
appears to support the contention of a more generalized 
executive system. Zelazo et al. conclude that “a review of 
the literature on the early development of EF reveals 
 converging evidence for domain-general changes in all 
aspects of EF” (p. 198). In other words, although frac-
tionalization of the executive system is possible on a 
 conceptual basis, it is ecologically nonexistent as these 
component parts never operate independently. 
 TOWARD A MODEL OF EXECUTIVE CONTROL 
AND ITS DEVELOPMENT 
When we speak about executive control, we are speaking 
about a complex integrated network that is truly different 
and greater than the sum of its parts (Miyake & Shah, 
1999). It appears as if the development of this integrated 
system takes some time and that children do not exert 
executive control in the same manner as do adults. 
“Attentional control appears to emerge in infancy and 
develop rapidly in early childhood. In contrast, cognitive 
flexibility, goal setting, and information processing expe-
rience a critical period of development between 7 and 9 
years of age, and are relatively mature by 12 years of age. 
A transitional period is thought to occur at the beginning 
of adolescence, and shortly after ‘executive control’ is 
likely to emerge” (Anderson, 2002, p.71). The emergence 
of executive control can be characterized as the full inte-
gration of a number of subsystems that have neotogeni-
cally been moving toward integration for some time.
The concept of a CE is not new (Baddeley & Hitch, 
1974 ). Its critics, including Baddeley himself, noted that 
the CE may have almost become synonymous with a 
grab-bag of all functions not attributable to the periph-
eral slave systems. Donald (1991) noted “that the central 
executive is a hypothetical entity that sits on top of the 
mountain of attention and working memory like some 
gigantic Buddha, an inscrutable immaterial and omni-
present homunculus at whose busy desk the buck stops 
every time attention and memory theorists run out of 
alternatives” (p. 327). The concept of CE requires neither 
Buddha nor slaves. It can be viewed as the integration of 
