systems designed to regulate increasing complex behav-
ior. There are computational models of working memory 
that describe the operation of such an integrated model 
(Hazy, Frank, & O’Reilly, 2006, 2007). The CE can be 
considered the efficiency of a complex interconnected 
system that has developed consistently with connectionist 
learning principles through its interaction with reward 
and arousal mechanisms and that has continued to 
develop and be refined for more than two decades. We 
believe the CE reflects the information-processing effi-
ciency related to the white-matter connectivity between 
various EF structural components.
We believe that a model that conceptualizes complex 
executive control/regulatory systems from its beginning 
in response inhibition (Koziol & Budding, 2009) and 
 subsequent development through increasingly intercon-
nected small-world networks, inclusive of arousal and 
reinforcement systems, has significant value for under-
standing issues involved with the development and assess-
ment of EF. More specifically, we propose a model that 
has the development of complex executive regulation 
reflective of the neotenic development of the component 
parts of the executive control system ranging from the 
early-arriving primary response inhibition circuits 
(Koziol & Budding) to the late-developing prefrontal 
cortex, which is not fully developed until well into the 
third decade of life (Fuster, 2002). We propose a blended 
model that hypothesizes that the basis for primary  circuits 
and interconnections for executive control are in place 
early on. These connections are rudimentary and reflect a 
state before synaptic pruning, and connectionist strength-
ening defines the efficiency of the circuit (Della Sala 
et al., 1998). We also propose that the components of the 
circuit develop increasingly complex interconnections 
during an extended period of time and that the interac-
tions of the components vary as a function of where in 
the developmental sequence an individual is (Anderson, 
2002). We propose that a connectionist small-world 
 network cognitive model (Bullmore & Sporns, 2009) 
mapped on to the neotenic development of network archi-
tecture would be a good point of departure to base future 
research on the development of EF/control/regulation. 
The adoption of such a model would have a number 
of implications, some of which are: Research should 
focus on the development and integration of the network. 
We need to understand what the developmental sequence 
is and how EF is manifested at specific checkpoints in the 
sequence of development. We need to understand if we 
are looking at the variation of a normal developmental 
process or a fractionalized component. 
In the evaluation of EF in adults, we believe that frac-
tionalization and assessment of the various components 
may not in general be advisable, while in the assessment 
of EF in children, it may be necessary. This is particularly 
true if at early certain stages, components of the circuit 
operate more independently than they will when the 
 circuit is fully expressed (Anderson, 2002). Being able to 
assess components in pediatric populations might allow 
for targeted intervention strategies to strengthen neural 
connections necessary for advanced integration of 
specific skills. 
There are some basic steps that should be taken to put 
neuropsychology on firm footing to move forward in 
investigating the central executive. The most fundamental 
is solving the problem of definition. Bridgman (1959) 
notes the definition stage is probably the most important 
stage in the research process as it specifies objectives, 
which are the purpose for conducting the research. More 
specifically, it narrows broad and vague ideas into 
 manageable, specific difficulties to be solved. Definition 
isolates and identifies the problem rather than the symp-
toms. Research proceeds from definition, and without an 
agreed-upon definition of EF and CE, it is difficult to see 
how coherent or meaningful research can go forward. We 
should attempt to align our definition of these constructs 
with a viable model of cognitive processing that reflects 
current research. We believe the model outlined here 
would be a reasonable first step toward such a universally 
endorsed definition.
We must recalibrate or perhaps reconfigure our neuro-
psychological tests so that we understand what it is that 
they are measuring. Along with this step, we should 
 continue to develop our understanding of the neural 
 circuitry of cognition and assess how our instruments tap 
that neural circuitry function.
We must decide whether we should continue to assess 
and measure the fractionalized components of EF or 
attempt to assess the integrated functioning of the system. 
There appears to be an increasing body of theoretical 
modeling of cognitive networks that suggest general 
interdependent functioning of the component parts of 
the system. Even if we can identify small-world-based 
nodes and assess only the independent functioning of 
that node, we have very little data that suggest that 
 repairing that node or improving its connectivity and 
functioning will improve the functioning of the executive 
system as a whole in an ecologically valid manner.
We must reconsider our nomothetically based assess-
ment practices in the light of data that suggest the 
 protracted period of development of the executive  control 
systems and their underlying neural architecture. We do 
not know from nomothetic test performance whether a 
discrepant score on a test during this protracted period 
represents a deficit score or merely an idiosyncratic but 
normally occurring developmental lag. Developmental 
psychologists have long discussed the idea of disorder 
and delay in terms of a delay representing functionally 
typical behavior of a chronological age younger than that 
of the child being assessed. A disorder represents a  cluster 
of behavior not typical at any age. A single nomothetic 
Downloaded by [George Mason University] at 03:47 06 January 2015 
INTEGRATED MODEL OF EF IN CHILDREN  95
test or even a small grouping of tests will not provide this 
information. We must have a thorough understanding of 
what constitutes typically developing executive control at 
specific ages to understand when a pattern of behavior is 
discrepant as opposed to delayed. 
Neuropsychology does not have to do this work inde-
pendently of other fields. Developmental psychology has 
a rich tradition in the study of the development and func-
tionality of executive control, for example. Zhou, Chen, and 
Mein (2012) point out “that effortful control … and EF 
are 2 constructs related to children’s self-regulation that 
have historically been the subject of research in separate 
fields, with EC primarily the focus of temperament 
research and EF the focus of cognitive neuroscience and 
clinical psychology” (p. 112). Their review indicated sub-
stantial similarities and considerable overlap in the defini-
tions, core components, and measurement of executive 
control and EF.

